                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "How can an Indian citizen register a company in the UK?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "An Indian individual or Indian company can incorporate a UK Private Limited Company through Companies House WebFiling, typically via an Authorised Corporate Service Provider (ACSP). The Indian leg goes through the FEMA Overseas Investment Rules 2022 via an Authorized Dealer Category-I bank. No UK residency is required for directors. Since 18 November 2025, all new directors and Persons with Significant Control must complete identity verification under the ECCT Act 2023, which the ACSP can handle remotely." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "How much does it cost to register a UK Limited Company?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "From 1 February 2026, Companies House charges GBP 100 for digital incorporation (up from GBP 50), GBP 156 for same-day digital incorporation and GBP 124 for paper incorporation. Add an Authorised Corporate Service Provider fee for ID verification and registered office (typically GBP 400 to GBP 800 first year), plus India advisory and FEMA ODI execution starting INR 24,999 + INR 49,999 indicatively. Binding quote confirmed after the discovery call and structuring memo." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "How long does it take to register a company in the UK?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Companies House online incorporation typically completes within 1 to 2 working days. Same-day digital incorporation is available for GBP 156. ECCT 2023 identity verification of Indian directors and PSCs adds 3 to 7 working days through an ACSP. End-to-end including UK bank account opening and India-side FEMA ODI usually runs 4 to 8 weeks." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "What is the corporate tax rate in UK in 2026?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "UK Corporation Tax has three tiers for financial years 2025-26 and 2026-27. The Small Profits Rate is 19 percent on profits up to GBP 50,000. The Main Rate is 25 percent on profits above GBP 250,000. Profits in the GBP 50,000 to GBP 250,000 band are subject to Marginal Relief, producing an effective rate that scales up to 26.5 percent (fraction 3/200). Close investment-holding companies are taxed at 25 percent on all profits regardless of profit level." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Do I need to be in the UK to register a company there?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "No. UK company registration through Companies House WebFiling is fully digital. Foreign founders, including Indian residents, do not need to travel to the UK for incorporation - an Authorised Corporate Service Provider (ACSP) can handle the entire process and ECCT 2023 identity verification remotely. An in-person UK visit may still be needed for traditional bank account opening with HSBC, Barclays or NatWest, but challenger banks like Wise Business, Revolut Business, Tide and Mettle accept remote KYC." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "Do I need a UK resident director for a UK Limited Company?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "No. The UK Companies Act 2006 does not require a UK-resident director for a private Limited Company. A director must be a natural person aged 16 or older and not disqualified, but can be of any nationality and reside in any country. This is a significant difference from Singapore (which requires a resident director) and makes the UK Ltd accessible to Indian founders without a nominee director arrangement." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "What is the ECCT Act 2023 and ID verification requirement?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act 2023 is the landmark UK reform expanding Companies House powers and introducing mandatory identity verification for company officers and Persons with Significant Control. From 18 November 2025, all new directors and PSCs must verify their identity at appointment - either directly via Companies House One Login or through an Authorised Corporate Service Provider (ACSP). Existing officeholders have a 12-month transition with enforcement from 18 November 2026." }
            },
            {
                "@type": "Question",
                "name": "What is the India-UK DTAA status in 2026?",
                "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "The India-UK DTAA was signed 25 January 1993 and entered into force 25 October 1993. The 2012 Protocol was signed 30 October 2012 and effective from 27 December 2013. The MLI (Multilateral Convention) is in force for India from 1 October 2019 and effective for India's DTAAs (including UK) from 1 April 2020 with HMRC Synthesised Text published 12 October 2022. The Principal Purpose Test under Article 7 of MLI applies. CBDT Circular 01/2025 dated 21 January 2025 confirms PPT applies prospectively." }
            }
        ]
