<!-- SECTION 4: WHO CAN FILE -->
<section class="content-section" id="who-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Who Should Use a UK Ltd Structure (and Who Should Not)</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <p>A UK Ltd is HIGH-VALUE for the following Delhi-NCR profiles:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Indian SaaS founders entering the UK or EU market:</strong> UK Ltd is the standard billing entity for UK / EU customers and supports VAT registration once turnover crosses GBP 90,000.</li>
                    <li><strong>Indian e-commerce sellers using Amazon UK, Shopify or other marketplaces:</strong> A UK Ltd simplifies VAT (Amazon FBA), payment processor onboarding and customer trust signals.</li>
                    <li><strong>Indian services firms targeting UK and EU clients:</strong> English-language contracts and UK courts simplify enforcement (consulting, design, marketing).</li>
                    <li><strong>Indian HNIs and family offices:</strong> Holding UK property or operating businesses through a Ltd corporate vehicle.</li>
                    <li><strong>Indian founders raising from UK or EU VCs:</strong> UK Ltd or US Delaware C-Corp is typically the expected vehicle.</li>
                    <li><strong>Treaty-eligible holding structures:</strong> India-UK DTAA with MLI PPT provides reasonable withholding tax outcomes on royalty, interest and dividend flows.</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top:16px;"><strong>NOT optimal for:</strong> Tax-arbitrage structures (UK CT tops at 25% with Marginal Relief band effective up to 26.5% - not a low-tax jurisdiction); pure offshore holding (UK Ltd is tax-resident corporate body with full domestic tax exposure - unlike Cayman or BVI); round-tripping back into India (explicitly prohibited under FEMA OI Rules 2022); resident-individual investment under LRS in financial-services entities (not permitted; corporate ODI route required); structures where central management is in India (HMRC will treat the company as UK tax resident regardless, AND India's POEM rules under Section 6(3) may also apply, creating dual residence and treaty tie-breaker complexity).</p>

            </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

