<!-- SECTION 9: CHALLENGES -->
<section class="content-section" id="challenges-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Common Delhi-UK Challenges and Patron Solutions</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                <div class="table-responsive-wrapper">
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Impact</th><th>How Patron Accounting Solves It</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>ECCT 2023 ID Verification - mandatory from 18 Nov 2025</td><td>New directors and PSCs require verification at appointment; existing officeholders face enforcement from 18 Nov 2026. Indian founders without an in-person UK presence often struggle with the verification flow.</td><td>Patron's London ACSP partner conducts ID verification remotely via approved video-based KYC; batch-verifies all Indian directors and PSCs before incorporation; handles the 12-month transition verification for existing UK companies where Patron is engaged for ongoing compliance.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>UK Bank Account Opening</td><td>Traditional banks (HSBC, Barclays, NatWest) typically require an in-person UK visit and 4 to 6 weeks; foreign founders often face declines.</td><td>Patron pre-qualifies the application with the bank, prepares a clean source-of-funds story and routes most foreign-founder cases through Wise Business, Revolut Business, Tide or Mettle (challenger banks that accept remote KYC and onboard in 1 to 2 weeks). The challenger fallback is configured before incorporation, not after a decline.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>India-UK DTAA MLI PPT</td><td>In force from 1 April 2020 (India side) under the Synthesised Text published by HMRC and Indian MoF; treaty benefits can be denied where one of the principal purposes was tax benefit.</td><td>Patron builds a commercial purpose memo at the outset documenting the UK / EU market entry rationale beyond tax. Aligns with CBDT Circular 01/2025 confirming PPT applies prospectively. The memo is designed for assessment defence under both PPT and GAAR.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>POEM under Section 6(3) Income Tax Act 1961</td><td>If effective management is in India, the UK Ltd may be treated as Indian tax resident, triggering dual residence and the DTAA tie-breaker analysis under Article 4.</td><td>UK-resident director chairs strategic board meetings; minutes signed in the UK; key contracts authorised by the UK board. Patron's POEM playbook calendar prevents inadvertent Indian tax residence. Where dual residence is unavoidable, the Article 4 tie-breaker (POEM test) is run with documentation aligned to the result.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Marginal Relief band - effective up to 26.5%</td><td>UK Corporation Tax effective rate climbs from 19% to 26.5% across the GBP 50,000 to GBP 250,000 profit band; planning around the GBP 50,000 threshold matters.</td><td>Patron projects annual chargeable profits at engagement and flags where reasonable salary, R&D claim or accounting period choices can keep profits below GBP 50,000 for the small profits rate. Where Marginal Relief applies, the 3/200 fraction is correctly computed in the CT600.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>FEMA Section 13 penalties</td><td>Up to 3 times the sum involved (where quantifiable) plus INR 5,000 per day for continuing contravention - Form ODI Part II late filing or APR misses trigger these.</td><td>Patron's compliance calendar locks all three FEMA deadlines - Form ODI Part II within 30 days of remittance, APR by 31 December annually and Form OFC on disinvestment. Reminders 30 days before each due date.</td></tr>

                    </tbody>
                </table>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

