<!-- SECTION 15A: LEGAL FRAMEWORK -->
<section class="content-section">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <h2 class="section-title">Legal and Compliance Framework</h2>
            <div class="content-text">
                
                <p><strong>UK Primary Statute:</strong> Companies Act 2006.</p>
                <p><strong>UK Corporate Transparency Statute:</strong> Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act 2023 (ECCT).</p>
                <p><strong>UK Tax Statute:</strong> Corporation Tax Act 2009 (charging) + Corporation Tax Act 2010 (computation).</p>
                <p><strong>UK Corporation Tax Rates (FY 2025-26 + FY 2026-27):</strong> Small profits rate 19% on profits up to GBP 50,000; Main rate 25% on profits above GBP 250,000; Marginal Relief in band GBP 50,000-GBP 250,000 (fraction 3/200; effective rate up to 26.5%); close investment-holding companies taxed at 25% flat.</p>
                <p><strong>UK Regulator (Companies):</strong> Companies House (executive agency of the Department for Business and Trade).</p>
                <p><strong>UK Tax Authority:</strong> His Majesty's Revenue and Customs (HMRC).</p>
                <p><strong>UK Filing Portal:</strong> Companies House WebFiling and HMRC online services.</p>
                <p><strong>Companies House Government Fees (from 1 February 2026):</strong> Digital incorporation GBP 100; same-day digital GBP 156; paper incorporation GBP 124; digital Confirmation Statement GBP 50; paper Confirmation Statement GBP 110.</p>
                <p><strong>ECCT 2023 ID Verification Timeline:</strong> Mandatory for new directors and PSCs from 18 November 2025; existing officeholders 12-month transition (enforcement from 18 November 2026).</p>
                <p><strong>Indian Statute (Outbound):</strong> FEMA 1999 + Foreign Exchange Management (Overseas Investment) Rules 2022 + Regulations 2022 + Directions 2022, effective 22 August 2022.</p>
                <p><strong>India ODI Limit (Companies):</strong> 400% of net worth on automatic route.</p>
                <p><strong>India LRS Limit (Individuals):</strong> USD 250,000 per FY; financial-services entities NOT permitted under LRS.</p>
                <p><strong>Indian Forms:</strong> Form ODI Part I, Form ODI Part II (within 30 days), APR (by 31 December), Form OFC (disinvestment).</p>
                <p><strong>India-UK DTAA:</strong> Convention between UK and India signed 25 January 1993; entered into force 25 October 1993; effective in India from 1 January 1994 and in UK from 6 April 1994 (income tax / CGT) and 1 April 1994 (corporation tax).</p>
                <p><strong>India-UK DTAA 2012 Protocol:</strong> Signed 30 October 2012; in force 27 December 2013; effective in India from 27 December 2013.</p>
                <p><strong>MLI:</strong> India-UK DTAA is a Covered Tax Agreement; both countries signed MLI on 7 June 2017; MLI in force for India from 1 October 2019; effective for India's DTAAs (including UK) from FY 2020-21 (1 April 2020); HMRC published the Synthesised Text on 12 October 2022.</p>
                <p><strong>CBDT Guidance:</strong> Circular No. 01/2025 dated 21 January 2025 - PPT applies prospectively; pre-1 April 2017 grandfathered shares remain outside PPT scope.</p>
                <p><strong>Indian Anti-Avoidance:</strong> GAAR - Income Tax Act 1961 Chapter X-A (Sections 95 to 102); POEM - Section 6(3); SEP - Explanation 2A to Section 9(1)(i).</p>
                <p><strong>Penalty (FEMA Section 13):</strong> Up to 3 times the sum involved (where quantifiable) plus INR 5,000 per day for continuing contravention.</p>
                <p><strong>UK Annual Compliance:</strong> Confirmation Statement annually; Annual Accounts to Companies House within 9 months of FY end (small / micro entity exemptions apply); CT600 to HMRC within 12 months of accounting period end; CT payment 9 months and 1 day after period end.</p>
                <p><strong>VAT Registration:</strong> Mandatory if taxable turnover exceeds GBP 90,000 in any 12-month rolling period; voluntary registration available.</p>
                <p><strong>Authority for source verification:</strong> Companies House at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/companies-house" target="_blank" rel="noopener">gov.uk/companies-house</a>, HMRC at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/hm-revenue-customs" target="_blank" rel="noopener">gov.uk/hmrc</a>, HMRC India tax treaties hub at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/india-tax-treaties" target="_blank" rel="noopener">gov.uk India treaties</a>, RBI Master Direction on Overseas Investment at <a href="https://www.rbi.org.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">rbi.org.in</a>, CBDT Circular 01/2025 at <a href="https://www.incometaxindia.gov.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">incometaxindia.gov.in</a> and India Code at <a href="https://www.indiacode.nic.in" target="_blank" rel="noopener">indiacode.nic.in</a>.</p>

            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- FAQ SECTION -->
<section id="faq-section" class="content-section" style="background-color: #ffffff;">
    <div class="content-container">
        <div class="text-content">
            <div class="faq-expanded">
                <aside class="faq-expanded__aside">
                    <h2 class="faq-expanded__title">FAQs: Company Registration in UK from Delhi in Delhi</h2>
                    <p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about Company Registration in UK from Delhi for Delhi businesses, answered by our CA and CS team.</p>
                    @include('partials.faq-enquiry-form', ['enquiryLocation' => 'Delhi', 'enquiryService' => 'Company Registration in UK from Delhi in Delhi'])
                </aside>
                <div class="faq-expanded__list">
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How can an Indian citizen register a company in the UK?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>An Indian individual or Indian company can incorporate a UK Private Limited Company through Companies House WebFiling, typically via an Authorised Corporate Service Provider (ACSP). The Indian leg goes through the FEMA Overseas Investment Rules 2022 via an Authorized Dealer Category-I bank. No UK residency is required for directors. Since 18 November 2025, all new directors and Persons with Significant Control must complete identity verification under the ECCT Act 2023, which the ACSP can handle remotely.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How much does it cost to register a UK Limited Company?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>From 1 February 2026, Companies House charges GBP 100 for digital incorporation (up from GBP 50), GBP 156 for same-day digital incorporation and GBP 124 for paper incorporation. Add an Authorised Corporate Service Provider fee for ID verification and registered office (typically GBP 400 to GBP 800 first year), plus India advisory and FEMA ODI execution starting INR 24,999 + INR 49,999 indicatively. Binding quote confirmed after the discovery call and structuring memo.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How long does it take to register a company in the UK?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Companies House online incorporation typically completes within 1 to 2 working days. Same-day digital incorporation is available for GBP 156. ECCT 2023 identity verification of Indian directors and PSCs adds 3 to 7 working days through an ACSP. End-to-end including UK bank account opening and India-side FEMA ODI usually runs 4 to 8 weeks.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the corporate tax rate in UK in 2026?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>UK Corporation Tax has three tiers for financial years 2025-26 and 2026-27. The Small Profits Rate is 19 percent on profits up to GBP 50,000. The Main Rate is 25 percent on profits above GBP 250,000. Profits in the GBP 50,000 to GBP 250,000 band are subject to Marginal Relief, producing an effective rate that scales up to 26.5 percent (fraction 3/200). Close investment-holding companies are taxed at 25 percent on all profits regardless of profit level.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Do I need to be in the UK to register a company there?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>No. UK company registration through Companies House WebFiling is fully digital. Foreign founders, including Indian residents, do not need to travel to the UK for incorporation - an Authorised Corporate Service Provider (ACSP) can handle the entire process and ECCT 2023 identity verification remotely. An in-person UK visit may still be needed for traditional bank account opening with HSBC, Barclays or NatWest, but challenger banks like Wise Business, Revolut Business, Tide and Mettle accept remote KYC.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Do I need a UK resident director for a UK Limited Company?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>No. The UK Companies Act 2006 does not require a UK-resident director for a private Limited Company. A director must be a natural person aged 16 or older and not disqualified, but can be of any nationality and reside in any country. This is a significant difference from Singapore (which requires a resident director) and makes the UK Ltd accessible to Indian founders without a nominee director arrangement.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the ECCT Act 2023 and ID verification requirement?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>The Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act 2023 is the landmark UK reform expanding Companies House powers and introducing mandatory identity verification for company officers and Persons with Significant Control. From 18 November 2025, all new directors and PSCs must verify their identity at appointment - either directly via Companies House One Login or through an Authorised Corporate Service Provider (ACSP). Existing officeholders have a 12-month transition with enforcement from 18 November 2026.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the India-UK DTAA status in 2026?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>The India-UK DTAA was signed 25 January 1993 and entered into force 25 October 1993. The 2012 Protocol was signed 30 October 2012 and effective from 27 December 2013. The MLI (Multilateral Convention) is in force for India from 1 October 2019 and effective for India's DTAAs (including UK) from 1 April 2020 with HMRC Synthesised Text published 12 October 2022. The Principal Purpose Test under Article 7 of MLI applies. CBDT Circular 01/2025 dated 21 January 2025 confirms PPT applies prospectively.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Quick Answers -->
            <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top:32px;">
                <p><strong>Quick Answers</strong></p>
                <p><strong>Q: Standard UK corporate vehicle?</strong> A: Private Limited Company (Ltd) under Companies Act 2006.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: UK Corporation Tax (FY 25-26 + FY 26-27)?</strong> A: Small Profits 19% (up to GBP 50,000); Main 25% (above GBP 250,000); Marginal Relief band effective up to 26.5%.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Companies House incorporation timeline?</strong> A: 1-2 working days online; same-day available for GBP 156.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Government fees from 1 February 2026?</strong> A: Digital incorporation GBP 100; same-day digital GBP 156; Confirmation Statement annual GBP 50 digital.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Director residency?</strong> A: NO UK residency required; any nationality; minimum age 16; not disqualified.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Company secretary?</strong> A: NOT mandatory for private Ltd (Section 270 Companies Act 2006).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: ECCT ID Verification?</strong> A: Mandatory for new directors and PSCs from 18 Nov 2025; existing officeholders enforcement from 18 Nov 2026.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: DTAA status?</strong> A: India-UK DTAA 1993 in force since 25 Oct 1993; 2012 Protocol effective 27 Dec 2013; MLI PPT effective 1 April 2020 (India side).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: UK annual compliance?</strong> A: Confirmation Statement annually; Annual Accounts within 9 months of FY end; CT600 within 12 months; CT payment 9 months + 1 day after period end.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: VAT?</strong> A: Mandatory above GBP 90,000 turnover (2026/27 threshold); voluntary registration available.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: India outbound regime?</strong> A: FEMA Overseas Investment Rules 2022; Form ODI Part I, Part II (within 30 days), APR (by 31 Dec).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: ODI limits?</strong> A: Indian companies up to 400% of net worth (automatic route); resident individuals LRS USD 250,000 per FY (no financial-services entities).</p>
                <p><strong>Q: FEMA Section 13 penalties?</strong> A: Up to 3x the sum involved + INR 5,000 per day for continuing contravention.</p>
                <p><strong>Q: Patron fee?</strong> A: Hub 05 cross-list - indicative bands INR 24,999 / INR 49,999 starting; binding quote after discovery call.</p>

            </div>
        </div>
